Sensor Fusion Project¶

Task 1¶

  • (a) Task 1a consists of understanding what the data represents. That will be covered in the report, and is not detailed in this Jupyter notebook.
  • (b) Task 1b involves determining the bias and variance of the gyroscope.

The sensor model for the gyroscope is in the form of $\mathbf{y} = \mathbf{G} \mathbf{\omega} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{r}$, where each individual measurement $\mathbf{y}_n \in \mathbb{R}^{3}$.

I have used Dataset 2 for the project. There's a variable named datasetNumber that represents which dataset was used for the assignment.

Finding the bias and variance¶

Bias: The average along each axis is taken and subtracted from zero.
Variance: The variance along each axis

In [6]:
# bias
bx, by, bz = np.mean(wx), np.mean(wy), np.mean(wz)
# variance
sigma_x, sigma_y, sigma_z = np.var(wx), np.var(wy), np.var(wz)
In [7]:
# print the results
print(f'The bias of the gyroscope is -- b_x: {bx}, b_y: {by}, b_z: {bz}')
print(f'The variance of the gyroscope is -- w_x: {sigma_x}, w_y: {sigma_y}, w_z: {sigma_z}')

The bias of the gyroscope is -- b_x: 0.08586055555555555, b_y: 0.2221088888888889, b_z: -0.06465555555555555
The variance of the gyroscope is -- w_x: 0.037367024691358025, w_y: 0.12977254320987655, w_z: 0.03734869135802469

def valueToIndex(arr, val):
    return np.abs(arr - val).argmin()

def nanTrimmer(arr, slice1, slice2):
    arr_copy = np.copy(arr)
    for i, _ in enumerate(arr):
        condition = (i >= slice1[0] and i <= slice1[1]) or (i >= slice2[0] and i <= slice2[1])
        if not condition:
            arr_copy[i] = np.nan
    return arr_copy
In [14]:
# slicing the acceleration arrays based on timestamps
# these timestamps would vary for each dataset

# for example, the following line of code will provide a start index and an end index for the timespan 90 to 115 seconds
# a window of 25 seconds is used for each case 
# Except in the case of ax, where we use a window of 17 seconds for the up case and 20 seconds for the down case because
# it appears that the robot was not kept in the static position for long enough during the collection of this dataset
axu_start, axu_end = valueToIndex(t, 83), valueToIndex(t, 108)
axd_start, axd_end = valueToIndex(t, 50), valueToIndex(t, 75)
axu, axd = np.mean(ax[axu_start:axu_end]), np.mean(ax[axd_start:axd_end])

ayu_start, ayu_end = valueToIndex(t, 150), valueToIndex(t, 175)
ayd_start, ayd_end = valueToIndex(t, 112), valueToIndex(t, 137)
ayu, ayd = np.mean(ay[ayu_start:ayu_end]), np.mean(ay[ayd_start:ayd_end])

azu_start, azu_end = valueToIndex(t, 0), valueToIndex(t, 17)
azd_start, azd_end = valueToIndex(t, 25), valueToIndex(t, 45)
azu, azd = np.mean(az[azu_start:azu_end]), np.mean(az[azd_start:azd_end])

In [16]:
g = 1. # it's measured in gs, so no need to write g in this formula
kx_i = (axu - axd) / (2 * g)
ky_i = (ayu - ayd) / (2 * g)
kz_i = (azu - azd) / (2 * g)
kx, ky, kz = np.mean(kx_i), np.mean(ky_i), np.mean(kz_i)

bx_i = (axu + axd) / 2
by_i = (ayu + ayd) / 2
bz_i = (azu + azd) / 2
bx, by, bz = np.mean(bx_i), np.mean(by_i), np.mean(bz_i)

In [20]:
# Polynomial fitting over the data
p = np.polyfit(1./h, d, deg=1)
d_pred = np.polyval(p, 1./h)
print(f'The line that fits through the given points is y = ({p[0]}) x + ({p[1]})')

The line that fits through the given points is y = (6220.921692124549) x + (3.11427481572556)
In [21]:
plt.figure()
plt.scatter(1./h, d, label='datapoints')
plt.plot(1./h, d_pred, color='C1', label='regression')
plt.xlabel('1/height ($pixel^{-1}$)')
plt.ylabel('distance (cm)')
plt.title('Scatter plot and Linear Regression of distance against the inverse of height')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

In the above linear regression, and in accordance with equation (3) in the project guide, the gradient is $h_0 f$ and the bias is $b$. These can be obtained from the two coefficients found in the 1-d linear fit. The gradient (slope) is 6220.9217 and the bias is 3.1143.

print(f'The average time interval taken by the robot is {timeInterval} seconds for every 40 cm')
